        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 17-year-old Czech girl with a slender build and pale complexion, who presents to the adolescent psychiatry outpatient clinic in Prague accompanied by her mother. She is dressed in a dark hoodie and keeps her gaze mostly averted, speaking quietly and with long pauses. Over the past three to four weeks she has experienced a persistently low mood, marked loss of interest in activities she previously enjoyed — including playing the violin and reading graphic novels — profound fatigue, and difficulty falling asleep at night [PMID:36156484]. She reports waking at 3 a.m. most nights and being unable to return to sleep, often lying in bed ruminating. She acknowledges passive thoughts that life is not worth living but denies active suicidal ideation or plans [MEDDIALOG:F32.9:2].\n\nAt school, {patientName} is a diligent student in the second year of a gymnasium (grammar school) in Prague. Her grades have dropped noticeably over the past month; she struggles to concentrate during lessons and often cannot recall what she studied the night before [PMID:36156484]. She used to rehearse violin with a youth orchestra every Saturday, but has stopped attending since the depressive episode began. Her appetite has decreased significantly — she estimates eating about half her usual portions — and she has lost approximately 3 kg over six weeks.\n\n{patientName} lives with both parents and a younger brother in a flat in the Vinohrady district. Her mother describes her as previously cheerful and sociable, but notes that she has been increasingly withdrawn, spending most of her free time alone in her room and barely communicating with family members. Her small circle of friends has tried to include her in outings, but she consistently declines. She does not use alcohol or recreational drugs. She has no romantic relationship at present and reports no significant recent psychosocial stressor beyond general academic pressure, though she mentions feeling \"invisible\" and worrying that she disappoints her parents."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:01b45e15-3e7f-4449-976e-d320fb3ab1cf",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
